<!--To help us understand and resolve your issue, please fill out the form to the best of your ability. Feel free to delete the sections that do not apply.-->

**Description of the problem**

The setting of transparency will affect the pdf figure. 
I want to add some text to figure after I set  transparency  in the previous line. After transforming to PDF, the text will not be shown.
Before the official GMT 6.1, my test is ok. After I update to GMT 6.1, the problem shows up. 
The gs version is 9.28 (no bug for transparency ? ). 
<!-- Please be as detailed as you can when describing an issue. The more information we have, the easier it will be for us to track this down. -->

**Full script that generated the error**

<!-- It helps a lot if you share any data files required to run your script. You can drag-and-drop them here or paste a link to Dropbox/GoogleDrive/etc. -->

```
#!/usr/bin/env bash
#

gmt psbasemap -R2019-03-31T09:00:00/2019-04-01T09:15:00/3/9  -BnSeW -Bpxa4Hf1h -Bsxa1Df1D -Bpya1g1f0.5+l"1 Hz SSH/m" -JX5i/3i -K >swh.ps

echo 2019-03-31T14:20:00 3 >h5.d
echo 2019-03-31T14:20:00 9 >>h5.d
echo 2019-03-31T16:10:00 9 >>h5.d
echo 2019-03-31T16:10:00 3 >>h5.d
gmt psxy  h5.d -R2019-03-31T09:00:00/2019-04-01T09:00:00/3/9 -JX  -W1p,red, -Gred -t90 -O -K >> swh.ps

echo 2019-03-31T11:08:27 3 >h5.d
echo 2019-03-31T11:08:27 9 >>h5.d
echo 2019-03-31T11:12:36 9 >>h5.d
echo 2019-03-31T11:12:36 3 >>h5.d
gmt psxy  h5.d -R2019-03-31T09:00:00/2019-04-01T09:00:00/3/9 -JX  -W1p,green, -Ggreen -t90 -O -K >> swh.ps

echo 2019-03-31T11:08:27 8.5 | gmt pstext -R2019-03-31T09:00:00/2019-04-01T09:00:00/3/9 -J -O -K -F+f10p,5+jBR+t"AIRAS"  >> swh.ps
echo 2019-03-31T16:00:00 8.5 | gmt pstext -R2019-03-31T09:00:00/2019-04-01T09:00:00/3/9 -J -O  -F+f10p,5+jBL+t"BUOY@-1@-@ MOVING"  >> swh.ps

gmt psconvert  swh.ps -P -Tf -A
rm gmt.* *.d
```

**Full error message**

<!-- Tip: you'll get more detailed error messages if you add -Vd to your gmt commands. -->

```
# PASTE ERROR MESSAGE HERE

None
```

**Actual outcome**

<!--The output produced by the above script, which may be a screenshot, console output, etc.-->

**Expected outcome**

<!--A description of the expected outcome from the above script.-->

**System information**

* Operating system: MINGW64
* GMT version (`gmt --version`): 6.1.0 [64-bit]

comments_content.body:
ghostscript never released gs 9.28. Please confirm your gs version by running `gs --version`.

This is my output with GMT master + gs 9.50. It looks correct, right?
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3974108/89091956-aae82480-d37b-11ea-874e-4f3cf6a4959f.png)
Was just going to post the same result.  Most be gs issue.

en...
Could you tell me how to check the gs version under windows(MINGW64)?
The version [9.28rc](https://github.com/ArtifexSoftware/ghostpdl-downloads/releases/tag/gs928rc4) is released before 9.50.
The GMT always give me the information: 
`psconvert [WARNING]: Input file has transparency but your gs version 9.51 has a bug preventing it - please downgrade to 9.50`

But I did not use 9.51.

I am sure this is not gs issue. 
Because if I back to other gmt 6 version before the official release. It work again (means no the above problem).

Could someone test it under windows (MINGW64)?

Add `-Vd` to your psconvert command, then you should see some debug messages like
```
psconvert [DEBUG]: gmt_check_executable: Pass to popen: [gs --version 2> /dev/null]
psconvert [DEBUG]: gs --version 2> /dev/null was successful
psconvert [DEBUG]: Ghostscript version: 9.50
psconvert [INFORMATION]: Processing swh.ps...
psconvert [INFORMATION]: Find HiResBoundingBox ...
```


> The version [9.28rc](https://github.com/ArtifexSoftware/ghostpdl-downloads/releases/tag/gs928rc4) is released before 9.50.

It's a candidate release. Ghostscript planned to release 9.28 but actually released 9.50 instead.


> The GMT always give me the information:
psconvert [WARNING]: Input file has transparency but your gs version 9.51 has a bug preventing it - please downgrade to 9.50

The GMT official Windows installers ship ghostscript which may be newer than 9.50. It's possible that you're running the one shipped with GMT installers.

> I am sure this is not gs issue.
> Because if I back to other gmt 6 version before the official release. It work again (means no the above problem).

Please attach your PS file and also post your PNG file here, so that we can see what's the problem.

OK.
I found that in the GMT dir, there is gswin*.exe. This is the problem.
After delete it, the GMT calls my system gs. And it is fine.

So, it is clear.
Just a question?  Why ship gs under windows, since it is not perfect and always affects the transparency  setting.
Pretty sure @joa-quim added a working gs; he can address that tomorrow.

> Why ship gs under windows, since it is not perfect and always affects the transparency setting.

That is simply not true. This is what I get with your script. Together with the warning message
```
bash scri.sh
psconvert [WARNING]: Input file has transparency but your gs version 9.51 has a bug preventing it - please downgrade to 9.50
```
The warning message started to show up when we satarted to check the gs version number. It happens that I built ghostscript from source a little after they released 9.50. At that time the breaking transparency was not yet in the code but the version number had already been increased. We need to do something about it but the shipped in gs has been there since 6.0 and w had no complains so far (not countong this one ofc).

![swh](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/537321/89109275-a4b77e00-d437-11ea-89a1-2226e280084f.png)
Compared to my plot in https://github.com/GenericMappingTools/gmt/issues/3798#issuecomment-667453273, the text strings `AIRAS` and `BOUY1MOVING` are not plotted.
Yes, I noticed it but that's separate from transparency

It's in the PS though, which in gsview6 also displays the transparency.
Have no time for the moment to explore this further (screen capture from ghostview bellow)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/537321/89109576-6a031500-d43a-11ea-876d-45e067cdf13f.png)

Thanks @joa-quim, you got the same result with me. The ps file could show the added text. The pdf converted by `psconvert` will not show it.
Exactly，I should say the setting of transparency will affect the `psconvert` tool. The transparency itself is not affected in the pdf figure. It is the GMT shell lines after setting transparency affected and could not be converted to pdf or png.

It is related to the  GMT build-in `gs` (official GMT 6.1).
Yes, something is not working but the distributed GS is exactly the same as it was for 6.0 and you say that it sop working only after 6.1

For the upcoming GMT 6.1.1 release, I think what we can do is to distribute gs 9.50 in the Windows installers, as gs's master branch also means unstable, and it's annoying to see the `psconvert [WARNING]: Input file has transparency but your gs version 9.51 has a bug preventing it - please downgrade to 9.50` even though the gs may work.

OK, tried with the new 9.53 RC and it works but I also get these weird messages
```
   **** WARNING: .setopcaityalpha is deprecated (as of 9.53) and will be removed in a future release
   **** See .setfillconstantalpha/.setalphaisshape for the improved solution
   **** WARNING: .setopcaityalpha is deprecated (as of 9.53) and will be removed in a future release
   **** See .setfillconstantalpha/.setalphaisshape for the improved solution
   **** WARNING: .setopcaityalpha is deprecated (as of 9.53) and will be removed in a future release
   **** See .setfillconstantalpha/.setalphaisshape for the improved solution
   **** WARNING: .setopcaityalpha is deprecated (as of 9.53) and will be removed in a future release
   **** See .setfillconstantalpha/.setalphaisshape for the improved solution
```
I say weird because the only place I find reference to that offense in in the source code itself. *e.g.* in ``ghostscript\Resource\Init\pdf_main.ps``
Yes, we will have to rewrite how we use the transparency operators.
We just released GMT 6.1.1, and the Windows installers now ship a working ghostscript. Closing the issue.
